A bill seeking to establish the National Student Financial Aid Scheme scaled second reading in the Senate yesterday. The bill, sponsored by Senator Sadiq Sulieman Umar, (APC, Kwara North), seeks to provide a realistic framework for the success of education financing. Umar, in his lead debate, said the Bill provided for the management, governance and administration of the proposed scheme. According to him, the National Student Financial Aid Scheme, upon its establishment, would grant interest free loans and bursary to eligible undergraduates He added that it would also ensure the structured administration of such loans and bursary, including recovery. He recalled that the Nigeria Students Loans Board which was established in 1982 to help students finance undergraduate and graduate studies within and outside Nigeria, provided loans between 1972 and 1991 totaling N46 million to help students finance their education.   NIMASA man gets Rotary award     ‘Why youths need exportable skill set’     ‘More youth involvement in SDGs mobilisation…   He disclosed that out of the sum, the Board faced the problem of recovering outstanding loans of over N40 million, which led to the suspension of the scheme in 1992. He stated that the Students Loans Boards was replaced in 1993 by the Nigerian Education Bank. He explained that the Education Bank served as a major intermediary in education credit market financing, and designed to harness private sector resources for funding education. The Kwara North Senator noted that the bill to establish the National Students Financial Aid Scheme, also seeks to repeal the existing Nigerian Education Bank. Senators in their contributions supported the Bill. The Bill was referred by the Senate President, Ahmad Lawan, to the Committee on Tertiary Institutions and TETFUND for further legislative action.